Tutorial 1: Exploratory analysis of pharmacogenomic data

Alejandro Reyes

Introduction

Probably the most important step of analyzing datasets is to actually understand the data. This process is crucial to know what kind of questions we can answer with it. This tutorial has code that will help guiding you through this process. Make sure you understand well the experimental design of the two studies and try to link each variable to this experimental design. Also, make sure you understand what each R command is doing. Feel free to hack the code!

If you have any question about the code, ask! Also remember that google is one of the most important tool for data science.

Lets start by installing the package that contains the data.

One of the first things data scientists do when digging into new data is to explore their distributions. Histograms visualize the data distributions and can also point us towards appropiate statistical models. The code belowtransforms the data into a logarithmic scale and plots a histogram separately for each study. Based on these plots, which study would you say has the most consistent experimental protocol?

library(ggplot2)
ggplot( pharmacoData, aes( log2(concentration) ) ) +
    geom_histogram(fill = "white", colour="black") +
    facet_wrap(~study)
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

Viability scores are the percentage of cells that survive upon exposure to a certain drug. Below, we will explore the range of the data and calculate how many data points are below 0 and above 100.

range( pharmacoData$viability )
## [1] -20.0000 319.4919
sum( pharmacoData$viability < 0 )
## [1] 23
sum( pharmacoData$viability > 100 )
## [1] 15778

We can also compare the distribution of viability scores between the two studies using density plots. Based on the distribution of the viability scores, would you say there are obvious differences between the two studies?

ggplot( pharmacoData, aes( viability, group=study, colour=study) ) +
    geom_density(fill="white", lwd=2, alpha=0.1) + xlim(0, 170)
## Warning: Removed 86 rows containing non-finite values (stat_density).

The code below plots the viability scores as box-plots for each drug, stratified by the two studies. Can you tell something about the toxic properties of the different drugs? Are these properties consistent across studies?

ggplot( pharmacoData, aes( y=viability, x=drug, fill=study) ) +
    geom_boxplot() +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1, vjust=.5)) +
    ylim(0, 200)
## Warning: Removed 41 rows containing non-finite values (stat_boxplot).
